   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Indicators :
1.1 (1) Effective implementation of SC-JC Joint Regulation (Peraturan Bersama) and the proper functioning of the Working Committee for the improvement of a more impartial, accessible, independent, accountable and effective judiciary is established between the SC and Judicial Commission
1.1 (2) Monitoring System to share info between the internal oversight mechanism of the SC and the external oversight mechanism of the Judicial Commission is in place and implemented 
Annual Output Indicator:
Year 1. First step to bridge SC and JC relationship is completed   
Year 2. Mechanism to re-activate Working Committee is implemented
Year 3. Increased frequency of Working Committee meeting
Year 4. Working Committee is functioning and the monitoring system/data sharing is in place 
Year 5. Working Committee is functioning and the monitoring system is in place 

1.2 (1) Standard operating procedures and policies relating to internal oversight mechanism are in place and implemented
1.2 (2) N&#xB0; of external surveys conducted by CSOs based on improved instrument aimed at the development of quality improvement policies.
1.2 (3) External survey instrument to analyze the court services, jointly developed with the CSOs is enhanced and implemented
Annual Output Indicator:
Year 1. Comprehensive assessment report to improve SOPs and external survey is in place    
Year 2. Improved SOPs and external survey instruments on Internal Oversight mechanism is tested and in place
Year 3. Improved SOPs and external survey instruments on Internal Oversight mechanism is implemented
Year 4. Improved SOPs and external survey instruments on Internal Oversight mechanism is implemented
Year 5. Improved SOPs and external survey instruments on Internal Oversight mechanism is proposed to the Supreme Court  

1.3 Enhanced public complaint mechanism in pilot regions (7 or 8 pilots) to enable an investigation to be tracked and keep statistics on complaints and responses
Annual Output Indicator
Year 1</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2014">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">Baselines:
1.1. There used to be a Working Committee in 2011-2012 to link the interests of both institutions.  During this period, the committee issued four joint regulations to manage the code of conduct of judges.  Currently, there is no bridging unit to mediate any tensions between the two institutions. This situation underpins the importance of having a working unit that can bridge and nurture a good relationship between the two institutions.

1.2 The current workload of the High Court in the area of supervision is quite immense and faces many difficulties.  Furthermore, the current internal oversight procedure places a financial burden on the High Court which must provide funding to three Bawas members in Jakarta to travel to relevant regions for reporting reasons.   Under the revised draft bill of the Supreme Court law, the High Court is mandated to provide funding to one Bawas member only as well as two High Court oversight judges.  The change will result in savings for the High Court and improve the performance of Bawas because all 40 (forty) of its members can handle more reports;

High Court supervisory judges who should function as a bridge between the Supreme Court and district courts have been facing some constraints which hamper their duties, such as lack of staff and capacity gaps among personnel, limited budget allocations to conduct supervision, the absence of a special unit in the High Court that is responsible for conducting supervision,  and lack of standard procedures to do their duties;   

Bawas is subject to E-Audit from the Supreme Audit Board (BPK).  However Bawas, for various reasons, cannot apply a similar survey.   Bawas has also worked on the internal complaints mechanism for whistle blowers;  
Some aspects of the baseline survey implementation on judicial public service in the appointed regions need to be reviewed and refined according to recent developments. Survey implementation in the appointed regions has only been conducted once</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
